> 
> ### Name: Exam11.4
> ### Title: Example 11.4 - Split-Plot Count Data
> ### Aliases: Exam11.4
> 
> ### ** Examples
> 
> data(DataSet11.4)
> 
> if (requireNamespace("glmmTMB", quietly = TRUE)) {
+   fit_nb <- glmmTMB::glmmTMB(
+     count ~ a * b + (1 | block) + (1 | block:a),
+     family = glmmTMB::nbinom2(link = "log"),
+     data = DataSet11.4
+   )
+   summary(fit_nb)
+   emmeans::emmeans(fit_nb, specs = ~ a * b, type = "response")
+ 
+   if (requireNamespace("DHARMa", quietly = TRUE)) {
+     sim_res <- DHARMa::simulateResiduals(fit_nb, plot = FALSE)
+     DHARMa::testDispersion(sim_res)
+   }
+ 
+   if (requireNamespace("report", quietly = TRUE)) {
+     report::report(fit_nb)
+   }
+ }
We fitted a negative-binomial mixed model (estimated using ML and nlminb
optimizer) to predict count with a and b (formula: count ~ a * b). The model
included block as random effects (formula: list(~1 | block, ~1 | block:a)). The
model's intercept, corresponding to a = 1 and b = 1, is at 2.37 (95% CI [2.06,
2.68], p < .001). Within this model:

  - The effect of a [2] is statistically significant and positive (beta = 0.41,
95% CI [0.03, 0.80], p = 0.036)
  - The effect of a [3] is statistically significant and positive (beta = 0.70,
95% CI [0.34, 1.07], p < .001)
  - The effect of a [4] is statistically significant and positive (beta = 0.92,
95% CI [0.57, 1.27], p < .001)
  - The effect of a [5] is statistically significant and positive (beta = 1.11,
95% CI [0.76, 1.45], p < .001)
  - The effect of a [6] is statistically significant and positive (beta = 1.26,
95% CI [0.92, 1.60], p < .001)
  - The effect of a [7] is statistically significant and positive (beta = 1.40,
95% CI [1.07, 1.74], p < .001)
  - The effect of b [2] is statistically non-significant and negative (beta =
-0.21, 95% CI [-0.65, 0.24], p = 0.366)
  - The effect of b [3] is statistically significant and positive (beta = 0.61,
95% CI [0.24, 0.98], p = 0.001)
  - The effect of b [4] is statistically significant and negative (beta = -0.50,
95% CI [-0.99, -0.02], p = 0.043)
  - The effect of a [2] × b [2] is statistically non-significant and positive
(beta = 0.07, 95% CI [-0.50, 0.65], p = 0.798)
  - The effect of a [3] × b [2] is statistically non-significant and positive
(beta = 0.10, 95% CI [-0.44, 0.64], p = 0.726)
  - The effect of a [4] × b [2] is statistically non-significant and positive
(beta = 0.12, 95% CI [-0.40, 0.64], p = 0.656)
  - The effect of a [5] × b [2] is statistically non-significant and positive
(beta = 0.13, 95% CI [-0.38, 0.64], p = 0.607)
  - The effect of a [6] × b [2] is statistically non-significant and positive
(beta = 0.13, 95% CI [-0.37, 0.63], p = 0.610)
  - The effect of a [7] × b [2] is statistically non-significant and positive
(beta = 0.13, 95% CI [-0.37, 0.62], p = 0.610)
  - The effect of a [2] × b [3] is statistically non-significant and negative
(beta = -0.38, 95% CI [-0.87, 0.12], p = 0.136)
  - The effect of a [3] × b [3] is statistically significant and negative (beta =
-0.63, 95% CI [-1.11, -0.15], p = 0.009)
  - The effect of a [4] × b [3] is statistically significant and negative (beta =
-0.81, 95% CI [-1.28, -0.35], p < .001)
  - The effect of a [5] × b [3] is statistically significant and negative (beta =
-0.98, 95% CI [-1.43, -0.52], p < .001)
  - The effect of a [6] × b [3] is statistically significant and negative (beta =
-1.10, 95% CI [-1.55, -0.65], p < .001)
  - The effect of a [7] × b [3] is statistically significant and negative (beta =
-1.21, 95% CI [-1.66, -0.76], p < .001)
  - The effect of a [2] × b [4] is statistically non-significant and negative
(beta = -0.12, 95% CI [-0.75, 0.52], p = 0.721)
  - The effect of a [3] × b [4] is statistically non-significant and negative
(beta = -0.23, 95% CI [-0.84, 0.39], p = 0.470)
  - The effect of a [4] × b [4] is statistically non-significant and negative
(beta = -0.29, 95% CI [-0.88, 0.31], p = 0.342)
  - The effect of a [5] × b [4] is statistically non-significant and negative
(beta = -0.32, 95% CI [-0.90, 0.26], p = 0.276)
  - The effect of a [6] × b [4] is statistically non-significant and negative
(beta = -0.35, 95% CI [-0.91, 0.22], p = 0.231)
  - The effect of a [7] × b [4] is statistically non-significant and negative
(beta = -0.36, 95% CI [-0.92, 0.20], p = 0.209)

Standardized parameters were obtained by fitting the model on a standardized
version of the dataset. 95% Confidence Intervals (CIs) and p-values were
computed using a Wald z-distribution approximation.
